						<div class="verses">
									<div id="vers153647" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">1</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Abiam, coming to the throne of Juda in the eighteenth year of Jeroboam,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153648" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">2</div>
						<div class="vers-content">reigned three years at Jerusalem. (His mother was called Maacha, daughter of Abessalom.<a href="" class="inline-comment" data-comment-id="511">âœ»</a> )</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153649" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">3</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Everywhere he followed the sinful example his father had set him, unworthy heir of David, that ever kept faith with the Lord his God.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153650" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">4</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Yet, for Davidâ€™s sake, the Lord suffered him to keep the lamp of the royal dynasty burning at Jerusalem; a son he must have to follow him, for the cityâ€™s preservation.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153651" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">5</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Such reward David had for doing the Lordâ€™s will, nor ever swerving, while life lasted, from his decrees, except in the matter of Urias the Hethite.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153652" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">6</div>
						<div class="vers-content">While Roboam lived, he was at war with Jeroboam,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153653" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">7</div>
						<div class="vers-content">and there was war, too, between Jeroboam and Abiam. What else Abiam did, all the history of his reign, is to be found in the Annals of the kings of Juda.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153654" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">8</div>
						<div class="vers-content">So Abiam was laid to rest with his fathers, with the Keep of David for his burying-place, and the throne passed to his son Asa.<span class="content-paragraph"><br><br></span></div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153655" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">9</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Asa, coming to the throne of Juda in the twentieth year of Jeroboam, reigned as king at Jerusalem for forty-one years.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153656" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">10</div>
						<div class="vers-content">His mother was called Maacha, daughter of Abessalom.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153657" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">11</div>
						<div class="vers-content">And Asa did the Lordâ€™s will, like king David, his ancestor,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153658" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">12</div>
						<div class="vers-content">ridding the land of shrine-prostitutes, and sweeping away all the filth of idolatry his fathers had brought in with them.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153659" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">13</div>
						<div class="vers-content">He even deprived his mother Maacha of her queenly rank, for her worship of Priapus and for dedicating a forest shrine to him; the grotto she had made he overthrew, broke the image and burnt the fragments of it and cast the ashes into the river Cedron.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153660" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">14</div>
						<div class="vers-content">He did not abolish the hill-shrines; but all his days his heart was true to the Lord;</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153661" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">15</div>
						<div class="vers-content">and he enriched the Lordâ€™s house with gold and silver and other offerings for its use, some dedicated by his father and some in performance of his own vows.<span class="content-paragraph"><br><br></span></div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153662" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">16</div>
						<div class="vers-content">This Asa and Baasa king of Israel were at war continually.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153663" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">17</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Baasa would not be content with his own Israelite territory; he invaded Juda and began making a fortified city of Rama, so as to deny Asaâ€™s subjects free passage.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153664" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">18</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Whereupon Asa took out all the silver and gold that was left in the treasure-chambers of temple and palace; this was to be conveyed by his messengers to Damascus, to Benadad, son of Tabremon, son of Hezion, king of Syria.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153665" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">19</div>
						<div class="vers-content">There is an alliance between us, he said, inherited from thy father and mine; witness these gifts of silver and gold I send thee. Do thou annul the treaty thou hast made with Baasa, king of Israel, and help me drive him out of my country.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153666" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">20</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Benadad, falling in with the request, sent out his generals with orders to attack the cities of Israel; Ahion they overcame, and Dan, and Abel Beth-Maacha, and all Cenneroth, till Nephthali had no land remaining.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153667" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">21</div>
						<div class="vers-content">So Baasa, when the news reached him, went back to Thersa, leaving the defences of Rama half finished;</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153668" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">22</div>
						<div class="vers-content">and the men of Juda, summoned by a royal decree which admitted of no denial, carried off all the stones and woodwork he had erected there; Asa made use of it to fortify Gabaa in Benjamin, and Maspha.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153669" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">23</div>
						<div class="vers-content">What else Asa did, the power he wielded, all his history, and the record of the cities he built, are to be found in the Annals of the kings of Juda. At last old age came upon him, and with old age, disease attacked his feet.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153670" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">24</div>
						<div class="vers-content">So he was laid to rest with his fathers, in the Keep of his ancestor David, and the throne passed to his son Josaphat.<span class="content-paragraph"><br><br></span></div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153671" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">25</div>
						<div class="vers-content">It was in the second year of Asa that Jeroboamâ€™s son Nadab came to the throne of Israel, and his reign over Israel lasted two years;</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153672" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">26</div>
						<div class="vers-content">he defied the Lordâ€™s will, following the evil example of his father, that sinned and taught Israel to sin.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153673" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">27</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Then, while he was laying siege to the Philistine city of Gebbethon, at the head of the Israelite army, Baasa son of Ahias, a man of Issachar, conspired against him and killed him there.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153674" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">28</div>
						<div class="vers-content">So, in the third year of Asa, Baasa succeeded Nadab as king.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153675" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">29</div>
						<div class="vers-content">And he, on coming to the throne, put all Jeroboamâ€™s kindred to death; not a man did he spare, so that the whole race perished, as the Lordâ€™s servant, Ahias the Silonite, had prophesied in his name.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153676" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">30</div>
						<div class="vers-content">So deep was Jeroboamâ€™s guilt, that sinned and taught Israel to sin; so was he punished for defying the Lord God of Israel.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153677" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">31</div>
						<div class="vers-content">What else Nadab did, all his history, is to be found in the Annals of the kings of Israel.<span class="content-paragraph"><br><br></span></div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153678" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">32</div>
						<div class="vers-content">It was this Baasa that was at war with Asa continually;</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153679" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">33</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Baasa, son of Ahias, who came to the throne in Asaâ€™s third year, and for twenty-four years reigned over Israel at Thersa.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153680" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">34</div>
						<div class="vers-content">He too defied the Lordâ€™s will, and followed the sinful ways by which Jeroboam taught Israel to sin.<span class="content-paragraph"><br><br></span></div>
					</div>
							</div>
